   Welcome to the AVIRIS (Airborne Visible/Infrared Imaging Spectrometer)
   Homepage. Please use the menu bar at the top to navigate through our
   site.
   AVIRIS is a proven instrument in the realm of Earth Remote Sensing. It
   is a unique optical sensor that delivers calibrated images of the
   upwelling spectral radiance in 224 contiguous spectral channels (bands)
   with wavelengths from 400 to 2500 nanometers. The instrument flies
   aboard a NASA ER-2 airplane (a U2 plane, modified for increased
   performance) at approximately 20 km above sea level, at about 730
   km/hr. AVIRIS has flown North America, Europe, portions of South
   America, and most recently, Argentina.
   The main objective of the AVIRIS project is to identify, measure, and
   monitor constituents of the Earth's surface and atmosphere based on
   molecular absorption and particle scattering signatures. Research with
   AVIRIS data is predominantly focused on understanding processes related
   to the global environment and climate change. [spacer.gif]
